204
00:20:11,200 --> 00:20:18,210
Now it was Friday morning. He made some coffee
and, as he drank it, watched the busy French

205
00:20:18,210 --> 00:20:19,780
Quarter through his window.

206
00:20:19,780 --> 00:20:28,830
What was it he had to do? Oh, yes, phone Gavin.
On Monday he was going to Washington for a

207
00:20:28,830 --> 00:20:35,710
conference about constitutional law. He and
his old friend Gavin Verheek were going to

208
00:20:35,710 --> 00:20:43,250
meet and get drunk together on Monday evening.
Gavin had been a friend ever since law school.

209
00:20:43,250 --> 00:20:47,960
He and Callahan were the only two in their
year who refused to go into private practice

210
00:20:47,960 --> 00:20:56,669
and get rich. While Callahan had become a
teacher, Verheek had joined the FBI as a legal

211
00:20:56,669 --> 00:20:57,669
adviser.

212
00:20:57,669 --> 00:21:04,059
When Verheek came on the phone, he said, 'Thomas,
how are you?'

213
00:21:04,059 --> 00:21:08,660
'It's ten-thirty. I'm not dressed. I'm sitting
here in the French Quarter drinking coffee

214
00:21:08,660 --> 00:21:12,880
and watching the world outside. What are you
doing?'

215
00:21:12,880 --> 00:21:18,769
'Well, here it's eleven-thirty, and I haven't
left the office since they found the bodies

216
00:21:18,769 --> 00:21:20,049
on Wednesday morning.'

217
00:21:20,049 --> 00:21:28,520
'It makes me sick, Gavin. The President will
get two Nazis on to the Supreme Court. I suppose

218
00:21:28,520 --> 00:21:34,730
you've already seen the list. I bet your office
is already checking that they've lived good,

219
00:21:34,730 --> 00:21:43,070
clean lives. Go on, Gavin, tell me who's on
the list. I won't tell anyone else.'

220
00:21:43,070 --> 00:21:49,400
'No chance. I'll only tell you this: your
name's not on the list'

221
00:21:49,400 --> 00:21:51,260
'I'm so disappointed.'

222
00:21:51,260 --> 00:21:53,070
'How's the girl?'

223
00:21:53,070 --> 00:21:54,630
'Which one?'

224
00:21:54,630 --> 00:21:59,169
'Come on, Thomas. The girl?'

225
00:21:59,169 --> 00:22:07,360
'She's beautiful and brilliant and gentle.
Oh, and rich. She has red hair and the longest

226
00:22:07,360 --> 00:22:09,580
legs you've ever seen.'

227
00:22:09,580 --> 00:22:13,240
'Wow! What's her name?'

228
00:22:13,240 --> 00:22:18,940
'Darby Shaw. But I haven't seen her for a
couple of days. She's trying to solve the

229
00:22:18,940 --> 00:22:25,809
murders all by herself. Why don't you tell
me who did it, and then I can tell her and

230
00:22:25,809 --> 00:22:27,529
she'll come back to me?'

231
00:22:27,529 --> 00:22:33,350
'Don't you read the papers? We have no suspects.
Not one.'

232
00:22:33,350 --> 00:22:38,299
'At least I tried. Are we going to meet on
Monday?'

233
00:22:38,299 --> 00:22:44,150
'I hope so. Voyles wants us to work day and
night until the computers tell us who did

234
00:22:44,150 --> 00:22:45,240
it.'

235
00:22:45,240 --> 00:22:50,019
'I'll expect a full report on Monday, Gavin
- not just the gossip.'

236
00:22:50,019 --> 00:22:56,730
'Why don't you bring Darby? How old is she?
Nineteen?'

237
00:22:56,730 --> 00:23:03,029
'Twenty-four, and she's not invited. I'll
see you on Monday at seven p.m., in the usual

238
00:23:03,029 --> 00:23:05,269
restaurant. OK?'

239
00:23:05,269 --> 00:23:09,679
'OK. See you.'

240
00:23:09,679 --> 00:23:10,679
***

241
00:23:10,679 --> 00:23:15,519
Darby's enquiries had brought her to the court
in Lafayette. Of all the Supreme Court cases

242
00:23:15,519 --> 00:23:21,520
due to be heard in the next few months, there
was one that could explain the killings. She

243
00:23:21,520 --> 00:23:27,620
needed to see the court's files on the case.
When the clerk brought them to her table,

244
00:23:27,620 --> 00:23:36,930
however, her heart sank. There were lots of
files, each inches thick. The case was seven

245
00:23:36,930 --> 00:23:43,370
years old. Only one person was involved, but
he had hidden behind thirty-eight different

246
00:23:43,370 --> 00:23:50,480
businesses, which had used no fewer than fifteen
law firms over the last seven years.

247
00:23:50,480 --> 00:23:58,230
She pulled her chair in to the table and began
to work.

248
00:23:58,230 --> 00:24:04,470
CHAPTER FOUR
Ideas and Information

249
00:24:04,470 --> 00:24:10,910
The meeting East and Voyles had with Coal
and the President did not go well. Not only

250
00:24:10,910 --> 00:24:15,620
could they not report any progress, but they
had to admit that investigations like this

251
00:24:15,620 --> 00:24:22,740
could take many months. Then Coal handed Voyles
a list of eight possible members of the Supreme

252
00:24:22,740 --> 00:24:29,960
Court, two of whom would fill the places left
empty by Rosenberg and Jensen. 'We want a

253
00:24:29,960 --> 00:24:36,500
report on these people in ten days, Voyles,'
he said, 'and make sure the press doesn't

254
00:24:36,500 --> 00:24:38,659
get to hear about them.'

255
00:24:38,659 --> 00:24:46,759
'You know we can't promise that,' Voyles said.
'We can't guarantee no leaks. As soon as we

256
00:24:46,759 --> 00:24:50,930
start to dig around these people, someone
will realize what's going on.'

257
00:24:50,930 --> 00:24:59,750
'The FBI can't guarantee secrecy?' Coal said.
'You'd better keep this out of the papers,

258
00:24:59,750 --> 00:25:01,080
Voyles.'

259
00:25:01,080 --> 00:25:08,440
Voyles jumped out of his chair. 'Listen, Coal,'
he shouted. 'Why don't you investigate these

260
00:25:08,440 --> 00:25:13,309
people yourself? Don't start telling me what
to do.'

261
00:25:13,309 --> 00:25:20,500
The President tried to make peace. 'All we're
saying is do your best, Voyles,' he said.

262
00:25:20,500 --> 00:25:27,559
'These people are young and they're good Republicans.
They'll be giving the Constitution shape long

263
00:25:27,559 --> 00:25:33,460
after I'm dead. So it's important to me that
the two who become members of the Supreme

264
00:25:33,460 --> 00:25:40,629
Court are clean, so that they can stay there
for ever. So no drugs, no unusual sexual habits

265
00:25:40,629 --> 00:25:43,840
- nothing like that. OK?'

266
00:25:43,840 --> 00:25:48,720
'Yes, Mr President. But we cannot guarantee
total secrecy.'

267
00:25:48,720 --> 00:25:54,710
'I understand. Just try your best.'

268
00:25:54,710 --> 00:25:58,340
'Yes, sir.'

269
00:25:58,340 --> 00:25:59,340
***

270
00:25:59,340 --> 00:26:03,679
Callahan went round to Darby's apartment with
a pizza and a bottle of wine. He hadn't seen

271
00:26:03,679 --> 00:26:07,909
her for four days. He rang on her doorbell.

272
00:26:07,909 --> 00:26:11,740
'Who is it?' she called through the door.

273
00:26:11,740 --> 00:26:17,200
'Thomas Callahan,' he said. 'Do you remember
me?'

274
00:26:17,200 --> 00:26:24,929
The door opened and Callahan stepped in. 'Are
we still friends?' he asked, and gave her

275
00:26:24,929 --> 00:26:26,200
a kiss.

276
00:26:26,200 --> 00:26:29,840
'Of course. I've just been busy.'

277
00:26:29,840 --> 00:26:33,370
'So what did the great detective find?'

278
00:26:33,370 --> 00:26:38,570
She was opening the bottle of wine and didn't
answer straight away. She poured wine into

279
00:26:38,570 --> 00:26:44,799
two glasses and they went and sat together
on the sofa. She put her legs up on to him,

280
00:26:44,799 --> 00:26:48,659
and he stroked them. He repeated the question.

281
00:26:48,659 --> 00:26:55,559
'Nothing, really. I was following a path,
and it took me somewhere. I even typed it

282
00:26:55,559 --> 00:26:59,909
up as a brief, but I don't think it's worth
anything.'

283
00:26:59,909 --> 00:27:04,710
'What? You've been running around playing
detective for four days, and refusing to see

284
00:27:04,710 --> 00:27:09,259
me, and now you're just going to throw it
away?'

285
00:27:09,259 --> 00:27:13,159
'It's over there on the table, if you want
to see it,' she said.

286
00:27:13,159 --> 00:27:21,990
'I don't want to see it now,' he said. 'We
have more important things to do. I'm going

287
00:27:21,990 --> 00:27:28,580
to be away in Washington for a few days, remember?
I'll read your brief and then we'll talk about

288
00:27:28,580 --> 00:27:34,299
it. But not till we've been to bed, OK?'

289
00:27:34,299 --> 00:27:38,700
She pulled him towards her and they kissed
long and hard.

290
00:27:38,700 --> 00:27:39,700
***

291
00:27:39,700 --> 00:27:46,820
There was a cleaner in the White House whom
everyone called Sarge. He was old, very black,

292
00:27:46,820 --> 00:27:52,659
and had white hair. He wore dark glasses all
the time, and everyone thought that he was

293
00:27:52,659 --> 00:27:54,760
half blind.

294
00:27:54,760 --> 00:28:03,140
In fact, Sarge could see very well. He could
see round corners. He had been working in

295
00:28:03,140 --> 00:28:11,570
the White House for thirty years now, cleaning
and listening, cleaning and seeing. He knew

296
00:28:11,570 --> 00:28:18,990
which doors stayed open and which walls were
thin. No one ever noticed him.

297
00:28:18,990 --> 00:28:27,000
His son Cleve was a policeman. This is how
it worked: Cleve would contact Gray Grantham

298
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:34,509
of the Washington Post and arrange a meeting.
Sarge and Grantham would meet. No one knew

299
00:28:34,509 --> 00:28:42,650
how Grantham got his political information,
but it was always good and always correct.

300
00:28:42,650 --> 00:28:48,470
Sarge never talked to anyone except Grantham,
and he didn't tell even him everything he

301
00:28:48,470 --> 00:28:49,840
found out.

302
00:28:49,840 --> 00:28:58,340
This time they met at Glenda's, a little cafe
on Fourteenth Street. Sarge was able to tell

303
00:28:58,340 --> 00:29:06,890
Grantham two of the people on the list of
possible Supreme Court judges.

304
00:29:06,890 --> 00:29:12,480
CHAPTER FIVE
An Implausible Theory

305
00:29:12,480 --> 00:29:18,460
Verheek had drunk too much the night before
with Callahan, as he had known he would. What

306
00:29:18,460 --> 00:29:26,230
had he said? Had he given away any secrets?
He remembered explaining that the connection

307
00:29:26,230 --> 00:29:32,960
between Rosenberg and Jensen was not political.
The connection was so obvious that for several

308
00:29:32,960 --> 00:29:36,139
days no one in the FBI had seen it.

309
00:29:36,139 --> 00:29:42,590
They were killed because the killer could
get to them. It was as simple as that. They

310
00:29:42,590 --> 00:29:48,419
weren't guarded as well as the others. Of
course this still didn't answer the question

311
00:29:48,419 --> 00:29:53,399
why someone wanted two Supreme Court judges
dead.

312
00:29:53,399 --> 00:29:57,480
He remembered that they spent most of the
evening talking about their student days together

313
00:29:57,480 --> 00:30:04,669
in Washington, and about women. Callahan had
given him a copy of the brief his girl-friend

314
00:30:04,669 --> 00:30:12,809
- what was her name? Darby - had written about
the death of the two judges. Callahan had

315
00:30:12,809 --> 00:30:20,720
said it was an interesting theory. She didn't
believe it, nor did he, but it was worth reading.

316
00:30:20,720 --> 00:30:27,220
Verheek pulled the brief out of his briefcase
now and started to read it. It was better

317
00:30:27,220 --> 00:30:33,620
written than most briefs, and he enjoyed it.
The theory was implausible, but no one else

318
00:30:33,620 --> 00:30:42,539
had thought of it. It was worth considering.
He would show it to Eric East.

319
00:30:42,539 --> 00:30:43,539
***

320
00:30:43,539 --> 00:30:50,409
The phone went four times, the answering machine
came on, but the caller left no message. The

321
00:30:50,409 --> 00:30:57,610
phone went again, and the same thing happened
again. The third time Grantham climbed out

322
00:30:57,610 --> 00:31:03,519
of bed and answered the phone. It was still
dark. 'Yes?'

323
00:31:03,519 --> 00:31:10,080
'Is that Gray Grantham, of the Washington
Post?'

324
00:31:10,080 --> 00:31:13,360
'It is. Who's calling?'

325
00:31:13,360 --> 00:31:17,490
'I can't give you my name.'

326
00:31:17,490 --> 00:31:19,970
'OK. Why are you calling?'

327
00:31:19,970 --> 00:31:26,429
'I saw your story yesterday about the White
House and the possible next two Supreme Court

328
00:31:26,429 --> 00:31:28,200
judges.'

329
00:31:28,200 --> 00:31:33,889
'Good. But why are you calling me so early
in the morning?'

330
00:31:33,889 --> 00:31:41,899
'I'm sorry. I'm in a pay phone. I'm on my
way to work. I can't call from home or the

331
00:31:41,899 --> 00:31:43,769
office.'

332
00:31:43,769 --> 00:31:45,749
'What kind of office?'

333
00:31:45,749 --> 00:31:48,749
'I'm a lawyer.'

334
00:31:48,749 --> 00:31:55,749
Great. Washington was home to half a million
lawyers. 'Private or government?'

335
00:31:55,749 --> 00:31:59,080
'I'd rather not say.'

336
00:31:59,080 --> 00:32:02,049
'OK. Anyway, why did you call?'

337
00:32:02,049 --> 00:32:09,890
A hesitation. 'I may know something about
Rosenberg and Jensen.'

338
00:32:09,890 --> 00:32:13,610
Grantham sat up straight. 'What, exactly?'

339
00:32:13,610 --> 00:32:16,590
'Are you recording this?'

340
00:32:16,590 --> 00:32:18,759
'No. Should I?'

341
00:32:18,759 --> 00:32:27,230
'I don't know, Mr Grantham. I'd prefer it
if you didn't record this. OK?'

342
00:32:27,230 --> 00:32:30,749
'Whatever you want. I'm listening.'

343
00:32:30,749 --> 00:32:32,620
'Can you trace this call?'

344
00:32:32,620 --> 00:32:38,169
'I could. But you're at a pay phone - what
difference would it make?'

345
00:32:38,169 --> 00:32:46,059
'You're right. I'm just frightened. You see,
I think I know who killed them.'

346
00:32:46,059 --> 00:32:51,049
Now Grantham was standing. 'That's valuable
information.'

347
00:32:51,049 --> 00:32:57,120
'It could get me killed. Do you think they're
following me?'

348
00:32:57,120 --> 00:33:00,330
'Who? Don't worry. Tell me your name.'

349
00:33:00,330 --> 00:33:02,289
'You can call me Garcia.'

350
00:33:02,289 --> 00:33:05,759
'That's not your real name, is it?

351
00:33:05,759 --> 00:33:09,630
'Of course not, but it's the best I can do.'

352
00:33:09,630 --> 00:33:14,370
'OK, Garcia, talk to me.'

353
00:33:14,370 --> 00:33:19,769
'I'm not certain, you understand. But I think
I accidentally saw something at the office

354
00:33:19,769 --> 00:33:21,659
that I was not supposed to see.'

355
00:33:21,659 --> 00:33:24,350
'Do you have a copy of it?'

356
00:33:24,350 --> 00:33:25,350
'Maybe.'

357
00:33:25,350 --> 00:33:28,730
'Do you want to talk or not?'

358
00:33:28,730 --> 00:33:34,700
'I don't know. What will you do if I tell
you something?'

359
00:33:34,700 --> 00:33:38,919
'First try to find out whether it's true.
We won't print the names of the killers of

360
00:33:38,919 --> 00:33:46,809
two Supreme Court judges in a hurry, believe
me.' There was a very long silence. 'Garcia,

361
00:33:46,809 --> 00:33:49,049
are you still there?'

362
00:33:49,049 --> 00:33:54,700
'Yes. I need to think about this. I might
call you later.'

363
00:33:54,700 --> 00:33:57,010
'OK, if that's what you want.'

364
00:33:57,010 --> 00:34:00,860
'Sorry I woke you up.'

365
00:34:00,860 --> 00:34:07,179
The phone went dead. Grantham pushed seven
numbers on his phone, waited, and then pushed

366
00:34:07,179 --> 00:34:14,609
six more. Another wait, and then four more.
The small screen on his phone showed him a

367
00:34:14,609 --> 00:34:26,250
row of numbers. He wrote them down on a piece
of paper. The pay phone was on Fifteenth Street.

368
00:34:26,250 --> 00:34:27,250
***

369
00:34:27,250 --> 00:34:32,690
East and K. O. Lewis, Voyles's second-in-command,
met with Coal alone, because the President

370
00:34:32,690 --> 00:34:39,560
was out of Washington. They had two bits of
information for him. First, they told him

371
00:34:39,560 --> 00:34:47,710
that cameras at the airport in Paris had recorded
the arrival from Dulles of the killer Khamel.

372
00:34:47,710 --> 00:34:53,960
Coal thought about this for a minute. 'What
if Khamel was involved in the killings? What

373
00:34:53,960 --> 00:34:56,400
does it mean?'

374
00:34:56,400 --> 00:35:03,160
'It means we'll never find him,' Lewis replied.
'Nine countries around the world have failed

375
00:35:03,160 --> 00:35:09,160
to find him for the last twenty years. It
means that he was paid a lot of money by someone

376
00:35:09,160 --> 00:35:12,369
or some people here to do the killings.'

377
00:35:12,369 --> 00:35:20,069
'So we know or we think that Khamel did the
killings, but it doesn't really help us, does

378
00:35:20,069 --> 00:35:21,069
it?'

379
00:35:21,069 --> 00:35:23,080
No, you're right.'

380
00:35:23,080 --> 00:35:27,400
'OK. What else have you got for me?'

381
00:35:27,400 --> 00:35:34,680
Lewis looked at East. 'There's no real progress
to report, except.

382
00:35:34,680 --> 00:35:36,920
'Except what?'

383
00:35:36,920 --> 00:35:43,590
'Well, there's this theory which has appeared
in the last twenty- four hours. A law student

384
00:35:43,590 --> 00:35:50,510
in New Orleans wrote it up as a brief. We
call it the Pelican Brief. Here's a copy of

385
00:35:50,510 --> 00:35:55,750
it. Voyles liked it, but he was afraid it
could hurt the President.'

386
00:35:55,750 --> 00:35:57,110
'How?'

387
00:35:57,110 --> 00:36:02,550
'Read it. You'll see.'

388
00:36:02,550 --> 00:36:03,550
***

389
00:36:03,550 --> 00:36:09,320
This time Garcia called Grantham during office
hours. He didn't tell him anything new. He

390
00:36:09,320 --> 00:36:12,960
was still frightened and uncertain.

391
00:36:12,960 --> 00:36:19,079
They agreed that he would call again at lunch-time
the next day. The call came from a pay phone

392
00:36:19,079 --> 00:36:21,910
on Pennsylvania Avenue.

393
00:36:21,910 --> 00:36:22,910
***

394
00:36:22,910 --> 00:36:30,710
Later, when the President returned, Coal told
him about the brief. 'The theory is implausible,'

395
00:36:30,710 --> 00:36:37,050
he said. 'But Voyles likes it. He probably
doesn't believe the theory any more than anyone

396
00:36:37,050 --> 00:36:44,010
else, but we've made him look bad over these
killings so far and he wants revenge. He's

397
00:36:44,010 --> 00:36:50,360
going to investigate this new suspect. If
the press get to hear about the investigation,

398
00:36:50,360 --> 00:36:54,690
that could be bad for you. We'd better do
something about it.'

399
00:36:54,690 --> 00:36:59,599
'Is the suspect someone we know?'

400
00:36:59,599 --> 00:37:04,650
'Yes.' Coal explained what was in the brief.

401
00:37:04,650 --> 00:37:07,630
'Did we get a lot of money from him?'

402
00:37:07,630 --> 00:37:14,600
'Millions, one way or another,' said Coal.
But the President preferred not to know the

403
00:37:14,600 --> 00:37:25,660
various ways in which money came in, especially
when they weren't always perfectly legal.

404
00:37:25,660 --> 00:37:30,559
CHAPTER SIX
Hunted!

405
00:37:30,559 --> 00:37:37,309
Thomas was drinking too much over dinner.
She didn't like it, and she told him so. He

406
00:37:37,309 --> 00:37:43,980
wanted to prove that she was wrong, so he
drank even more. They had an argument.

407
00:37:43,980 --> 00:37:49,940
After dinner, outside the restaurant, he pulled
the keys to his Porsche out of his pocket.

408
00:37:49,940 --> 00:37:56,369
'Thomas, no! You're too drunk to drive. Give
me the keys.'

409
00:37:56,369 --> 00:38:01,460
He held on to the keys and set off in the
direction of the car park. He couldn't walk

410
00:38:01,460 --> 00:38:07,550
straight and his foot kept slipping off the
pavement into the road. She followed him,

411
00:38:07,550 --> 00:38:14,119
but stayed some way behind; she was too angry,
and just wanted to get back to her apartment

412
00:38:14,119 --> 00:38:20,300
alone. He shouted something over his shoulder
about how he could drive better when he was

413
00:38:20,300 --> 00:38:23,180
drunk.

414
00:38:23,180 --> 00:38:27,290
She stood with her arms crossed on the other
side of the car park and watched him put the

415
00:38:27,290 --> 00:38:35,680
key into the lock. It took him three or four
attempts. Then he was inside and she lost

416
00:38:35,680 --> 00:38:42,400
sight of him between two other cars. She heard
him start the engine, though.

417
00:38:42,400 --> 00:38:48,920
The explosion knocked her to the ground. She
lay there for a moment, and then jumped to

418
00:38:48,920 --> 00:38:53,900
her feet. The Porsche was a ball of fire.

419
00:38:53,900 --> 00:38:59,580
Darby ran towards it, screaming his name.
Bits of the car were still falling all around

420
00:38:59,580 --> 00:39:06,349
her, and the heat stopped her thirty feet
away. She screamed with her hands over her

421
00:39:06,349 --> 00:39:07,349
mouth.

422
00:39:07,349 --> 00:39:13,460
A second explosion tore through the car and
pushed her back. She fell and her head hit

423
00:39:13,460 --> 00:39:19,210
the side of a parked car hard. Everything
went blank for a minute.

424
00:39:19,210 --> 00:39:22,839
Then there were people everywhere, and voices
shouting:

425
00:39:22,839 --> 00:39:28,990
'Whose car is it? Call 911! Was there anyone
in it?'

426
00:39:28,990 --> 00:39:35,180
She was repeating the name Thomas. Someone
put a cold cloth on her head. She heard the

427
00:39:35,180 --> 00:39:42,210
sound of the police and firemen coming, and
then there were red and blue lights everywhere.

428
00:39:42,210 --> 00:39:49,740
A black man was bending over her. 'Are you
all right, miss?' he asked.

429
00:39:49,740 --> 00:39:54,609
'Thomas,' she said. 'Where's Thomas?'

430
00:39:54,609 --> 00:40:00,570
'Miss, who's Thomas?' asked the man. 'Was
he in that car?'

431
00:40:00,570 --> 00:40:06,931
She nodded and then closed her eyes. She could
hear men shouting in the distance. They were

432
00:40:06,931 --> 00:40:14,540
all over by the burning car. She sat up and
was sick between her legs. Then she felt better.

433
00:40:14,540 --> 00:40:25,480
She got up and walked away. She knew who the
bomb had been for: her. And she knew why.

434
00:40:25,480 --> 00:40:31,810
She had to hide; they were hunting her. Were
they behind her even now? She wandered deep

435
00:40:31,810 --> 00:40:38,480
into the French Quarter, found a cheap hotel
and paid for a room with her card. As soon

436
00:40:38,480 --> 00:40:43,490
as she was in the room, she locked the door
and curled up on the bed with all the lights

437
00:40:43,490 --> 00:40:46,060
on.

438
00:40:46,060 --> 00:40:47,060
***

439
00:40:47,060 --> 00:40:52,369
Mrs Verheek answered the bedside phone. 'It's
for you, Gavin,' she called into the bathroom,

440
00:40:52,369 --> 00:40:54,569
where he was shaving.

441
00:40:54,569 --> 00:41:00,660
He came and took the phone from her. 'Hello,'
he said angrily. Who could be calling this

442
00:41:00,660 --> 00:41:02,330
early in the morning?

443
00:41:02,330 --> 00:41:06,799
'This is Darby Shaw. Do you know the name?'

444
00:41:06,799 --> 00:41:10,349
'Yes. We share a friend.'

445
00:41:10,349 --> 00:41:13,079
'Did you read the little theory I wrote?'

446
00:41:13,079 --> 00:41:16,990
'Yes, the Pelican Brief, as we call it.'

447
00:41:16,990 --> 00:41:20,760
'And who is "we"?'

448
00:41:20,760 --> 00:41:26,510
Verheek sat up straight. She was not calling
for a friendly chat. 'Why are you calling,

449
00:41:26,510 --> 00:41:27,510
Darby?'

450
00:41:27,510 --> 00:41:32,930
'I need some answers, Mr Verheek. I'm frightened
to death.'

451
00:41:32,930 --> 00:41:36,250
'It's Gavin, OK?'

452
00:41:36,250 --> 00:41:39,760
'OK, Gavin. Where's the brief?'

453
00:41:39,760 --> 00:41:42,220
'Why? What's wrong?'

454
00:41:42,220 --> 00:41:47,030
'I'll tell you in a minute. Just tell me what
you did with the brief.'

455
00:41:47,030 --> 00:41:52,450
'Well, I read it, and then I passed it on
to someone else, who passed it on to Denton

456
00:41:52,450 --> 00:41:54,890
Voyles, who liked it.'

457
00:41:54,890 --> 00:41:58,079
'Has anyone outside the FBI seen it?'

458
00:41:58,079 --> 00:42:00,380
'I can't answer that.'

459
00:42:00,380 --> 00:42:03,579
'Then I won't tell you what's happened to
Thomas.'

460
00:42:03,579 --> 00:42:10,140
'All right. Yes, it's been outside the FBI,
but I don't know exactly where and I don't

461
00:42:10,140 --> 00:42:12,390
know how many people have read it.'

462
00:42:12,390 --> 00:42:22,680
'He's dead, Gavin. He was murdered last night.
Someone put a bomb in the car. I was lucky.'

463
00:42:22,680 --> 00:42:27,589
Gavin was shocked. 'Where are you? Are you
safe?'

464
00:42:27,589 --> 00:42:33,970
'New Orleans. Who knows if I'm safe? They
must be after me too. It was me they really

465
00:42:33,970 --> 00:42:35,950
wanted.'

466
00:42:35,950 --> 00:42:40,880
'I'll have some men come and get you, Darby.
You can't stay on the streets. Then I'll catch

467
00:42:40,880 --> 00:42:43,750
a plane and I'll be there by midday.'

468
00:42:43,750 --> 00:42:49,630
'I don't think so. Thomas is dead because
he talked to you. Why should I want to talk

469
00:42:49,630 --> 00:42:55,119
to you? Give me your number at work. I may
call you later.'

470
00:42:55,119 --> 00:43:01,430
'OK. But Darby, just tell me: did he feel
any pain?'

471
00:43:01,430 --> 00:43:10,810
There were tears in her voice. 'No, it was
very quick.' Then she put the phone down.

472
00:43:10,810 --> 00:43:19,440
She could let herself cry now, because there
wouldn't be time later. Crying could get her

473
00:43:19,440 --> 00:43:21,810
killed.

474
00:43:21,810 --> 00:43:26,480
CHAPTER SEVEN
Keep Moving

475
00:43:26,480 --> 00:43:32,290
It was nearly time for the President's daily
meeting with Voyles. By now he was tired of

476
00:43:32,290 --> 00:43:39,190
the whole business; he just wanted to get
his men into the Supreme Court. Coal was telling

477
00:43:39,190 --> 00:43:46,380
him something, but he wasn't really listening.
Voyles and Coal hated each other so much now

478
00:43:46,380 --> 00:43:53,660
that Coal had to leave the office whenever
Voyles came. They had nearly fought last time.

479
00:43:53,660 --> 00:43:59,230
It didn't matter to Coal whether he was in
