01:14:55,791 --> 01:15:01,489
keep dying because of it. We'd better investigate
it. It must be Mattiece.'

840
01:15:01,489 --> 01:15:08,179
'I know,' Voyles said. 'We'll send down a
team of men, but I don't want the fool in

841
01:15:08,179 --> 01:15:14,159
the White House or Coal to hear that we're
investigating it - I want to surprise them.

842
01:15:14,159 --> 01:15:19,360
When the President told me to leave the brief
alone, I was carrying a small recorder in

843
01:15:19,360 --> 01:15:27,699
my pocket. I've got every word, loud and clear.
If we find that the brief is accurate, the

844
01:15:27,699 --> 01:15:33,380
press will love us, and we can let them know
that the President told us not to investigate

845
01:15:33,380 --> 01:15:34,380
it.'

846
01:15:34,380 --> 01:15:39,020
'That'll be the end of him and Coal,' Lewis
said happily.

847
01:15:39,020 --> 01:15:45,230
'I know. He'll have no chance in the election
next year. We've got him.'

848
01:15:45,230 --> 01:15:52,310
They smiled at each other. 'But what about
Mattiece?' Lewis said. 'If he hadn't killed

849
01:15:52,310 --> 01:15:57,900
all -those people, we wouldn't have thought
the brief was right. He must be crazy.'

850
01:15:57,900 --> 01:16:06,750
'There are rumours that he is,' Voyles replied.
'I've spoken to the CIA. They had men in New

851
01:16:06,750 --> 01:16:13,080
Orleans. They don't know where Mattiece is.
He's probably not in this country. He owns

852
01:16:13,080 --> 01:16:19,370
houses all over the world. We'll need their
help to get him. They were following the girl

853
01:16:19,370 --> 01:16:24,850
too, but they lost her in Chicago airport.
She could be anywhere by now.'

854
01:16:24,850 --> 01:16:33,630
'She could be dead,' Lewis said. 'Mattiece's
men are following her as well.' ***

855
01:16:33,630 --> 01:16:40,060
Grantham traced two old photographs of her
- one from her high school, one from her first

856
01:16:40,060 --> 01:16:45,940
university. He pinned them up beside his desk.
She was beautiful.

857
01:16:45,940 --> 01:16:51,050
She called him as she had promised. He had
read about the killing of a lawyer in New

858
01:16:51,050 --> 01:16:56,750
Orleans, and she told him the true story.
She also told him about the other killing,

859
01:16:56,750 --> 01:17:03,860
which had not appeared in the newspapers.
Then she said, 'Can you come to New York tomorrow,

860
01:17:03,860 --> 01:17:04,860
Grantham?'

861
01:17:04,860 --> 01:17:13,219
'Of course. It'll only take a few hours. But
please call me Gray.' He looked at the photographs

862
01:17:13,219 --> 01:17:14,840
of her.

863
01:17:14,840 --> 01:17:20,050
'I'll ring tomorrow morning to tell you where
to meet me. And tomorrow I'll tell you who

864
01:17:20,050 --> 01:17:22,420
killed Rosenberg and Jensen.'

865
01:17:22,420 --> 01:17:24,969
'Do you know who did it?'

866
01:17:24,969 --> 01:17:32,219
'I know who paid for the killings. I know
his name. I know his business and his politics.'

867
01:17:32,219 --> 01:17:34,969
'And you'll tell me tomorrow.'

868
01:17:34,969 --> 01:17:37,520
'If I'm still alive.'

869
01:17:37,520 --> 01:17:45,080
A pause. 'Perhaps we should talk immediately,'
he said. ***

870
01:17:45,080 --> 01:17:50,950
They met in her room in the St Moritz Hotel
in New York. They chatted for a while, getting

871
01:17:50,950 --> 01:17:57,130
to know each other. It was the first normal
conversation Darby had had for a week, and

872
01:17:57,130 --> 01:18:03,730
it was a great pleasure. They sent out for
some food, and after they had eaten he switched

873
01:18:03,730 --> 01:18:07,340
on a recorder and she told him a story:

874
01:18:07,340 --> 01:18:14,530
'For centuries, the Mississippi River has
been carrying mud down to the sea. Where the

875
01:18:14,530 --> 01:18:21,300
river meets the sea, marshes have spread out
over an enormous area. These marshes are the

876
01:18:21,300 --> 01:18:26,530
home for a great many rare and unusual animals,
birds, reptiles and fish.'

877
01:18:26,530 --> 01:18:35,590
'Then oil was discovered there in 1930. The
oil companies began to destroy the marshes.

878
01:18:35,590 --> 01:18:40,659
Where the river mud had been creating new
land, now the sea was able to wash the land

879
01:18:40,659 --> 01:18:46,870
away. Since the discovery of oil, tens of
thousands of acres of Louisiana marshland

880
01:18:46,870 --> 01:18:52,770
has gone. Every fourteen minutes, another
acre disappears under water.'

881
01:18:52,770 --> 01:19:01,290
'In 1979 an oil company owned by Victor Mattiece
found a very rich oilfield, worth thousands

882
01:19:01,290 --> 01:19:08,520
of millions of dollars. Mattiece wanted it
all. He knew that others would buy the surrounding

883
01:19:08,520 --> 01:19:15,080
land if they heard there was a major oilfield
there, so he pretended that nothing had happened.

884
01:19:15,080 --> 01:19:22,070
He stopped work there, and waited. Slowly
and patiently, as the years passed, he bought

885
01:19:22,070 --> 01:19:29,200
the surrounding land. He created new companies,
lots of them, so that no one would know that

886
01:19:29,200 --> 01:19:33,910
he was the buyer. At last he was ready to
begin drilling.'

887
01:19:33,910 --> 01:19:42,320
'Then a small environmental group called Green
Rescue made a legal request to the courts

888
01:19:42,320 --> 01:19:50,320
to stop the drilling. The request was un-expected,
because for so long Louisiana had profited

889
01:19:50,320 --> 01:19:56,900
from the oil companies. The court in Lafayette
agreed that all drilling should stop until

890
01:19:56,900 --> 01:19:58,050
the case was settled.'

891
01:19:58,050 --> 01:20:06,760
'Mattiece knew that this could take years.
He was dangerously angry. He spent weeks with

892
01:20:06,760 --> 01:20:14,610
his lawyers, making plans. But every move
they made was disallowed by the courts.'

893
01:20:14,610 --> 01:20:21,550
'People were sympathetic to Green Rescue's
case. A lot of wildlife was at risk. The marshland

894
01:20:21,550 --> 01:20:27,650
where Mattiece wanted to drill was home to
a great many rare and beautiful sea birds,

895
01:20:27,650 --> 01:20:34,870
including brown pelicans. There were very
few of these pelicans left. When people thought

896
01:20:34,870 --> 01:20:38,260
about the case, they thought about the pelicans.'

897
01:20:38,260 --> 01:20:47,200
'At last the case came to trial. Green Rescue
lost, and that was not surprising: Mattiece

898
01:20:47,200 --> 01:20:53,910
had spent millions of dollars and had the
best lawyers in the country. But the judge

899
01:20:53,910 --> 01:21:01,010
still forbade the drilling to start. The pelican
was a protected bird under Louisiana law,

900
01:21:01,010 --> 01:21:07,400
and Green Rescue weren't finished yet: they
would take the case all the way to the Supreme

901
01:21:07,400 --> 01:21:08,820
Court.'

902
01:21:08,820 --> 01:21:15,530
'How long would it take to reach the Supreme
Court?' Gray asked.

903
01:21:15,530 --> 01:21:17,889
'Between three and five years.'

904
01:21:17,889 --> 01:21:21,000
'By then Rosenberg would be dead anyway.'

905
01:21:21,000 --> 01:21:28,780
'Yes, but it might be a Democratic President
who was choosing the judge to take his place;

906
01:21:28,780 --> 01:21:37,420
Mattiece couldn't take that chance. And Jensen
was always soft on environmental cases. Mattiece

907
01:21:37,420 --> 01:21:44,170
needed two Republican judges in there, both
of whom were supporters of big business.'

908
01:21:44,170 --> 01:21:49,760
'Can you prove that all the companies involved
in buying the land in Louisiana are owned

909
01:21:49,760 --> 01:21:51,239
by Mattiece?'

910
01:21:51,239 --> 01:21:58,090
'It's in the brief, and I've written it all
out for you. And then there's the photograph.'

911
01:21:58,090 --> 01:22:00,110
'Tell me.'

912
01:22:00,110 --> 01:22:06,929
'Seven years ago, before the President was
elected, he was in New Orleans getting money

913
01:22:06,929 --> 01:22:14,480
for the Republicans. Although Mattiece stays
out of the public eye, he was there that day,

914
01:22:14,480 --> 01:22:21,190
and some clever photographer got a picture
of him shaking hands with the President. Both

915
01:22:21,190 --> 01:22:25,960
of them are smiling, and they look like old
friends. It's beautiful.'

916
01:22:25,960 --> 01:22:33,659
'I can easily find a copy of that. This whole
thing is beautiful. It's the biggest story

917
01:22:33,659 --> 01:22:41,420
since Watergate - maybe even bigger.' Gray
turned off the recorder and sat back in his

918
01:22:41,420 --> 01:22:49,460
chair. They were silent for a short while.
Then he asked, 'Do you think Mattiece himself

919
01:22:49,460 --> 01:22:52,300
chose Rosenberg and Jensen?'

920
01:22:52,300 --> 01:23:00,489
'No, I'm sure he had advice from a lawyer.
He's got lawyers all over the country.'

921
01:23:00,489 --> 01:23:05,310
Gray sat up again. 'Does he have any in Washington?'

922
01:23:05,310 --> 01:23:12,660
'Yes, there are two firms there who do some
work for him - Brim, Stearns and Kidlow is

923
01:23:12,660 --> 01:23:21,699
one of them; the other is White and Blazevich,
a very old, Republican firm. But why are you

924
01:23:21,699 --> 01:23:22,699
interested?'

925
01:23:22,699 --> 01:23:29,540
Gray quickly told her about Garcia. 'Maybe
he works at one of those two firms,' he said.

926
01:23:29,540 --> 01:23:33,540
'That would make it much easier to find him.'

927
01:23:33,540 --> 01:23:39,090
They were both tired. She asked him to sleep
on the sofa in her room that night, so that

928
01:23:39,090 --> 01:23:45,530
she could get a good night's sleep for the
first time for days. He agreed. She was so

929
01:23:45,530 --> 01:23:51,869
beautiful that he would do anything to be
close her; he would even sleep on a five-foot

930
01:23:51,869 --> 01:23:56,570
sofa.

931
01:23:56,570 --> 01:24:01,570
CHAPTER THIRTEEN
Washington

932
01:24:01,570 --> 01:24:07,840
Darby worked in the library all morning and
rang Grantham at midday. She had been reading

933
01:24:07,840 --> 01:24:13,190
lists of the members at both the Washington
law firms that worked for Mattiece; there

934
01:24:13,190 --> 01:24:19,280
was no one called Garcia on either list, of
course. There were four Spanish names among

935
01:24:19,280 --> 01:24:26,840
the 190 lawyers who worked for Brim, Stearns
and Kidlow, but none among the 412 who worked

936
01:24:26,840 --> 01:24:30,150
for White and Blazevich.

937
01:24:30,150 --> 01:24:36,100
She rang Gray with this information from a
pay phone in a cafe on Sixth Avenue. As she

938
01:24:36,100 --> 01:24:42,590
turned to leave she saw the short man who
had been looking for her in New Orleans. He

939
01:24:42,590 --> 01:24:50,610
was here, in New York, walking the streets.
He didn't look inside the cafe, however. For

940
01:24:50,610 --> 01:24:58,300
the moment she was safe, but it was time to
leave New York. Two hours later, she was at

941
01:24:58,300 --> 01:24:59,969
Newark airport.

942
01:24:59,969 --> 01:25:06,650
When this was all over - if she was still
alive - where could she go? She thought of

943
01:25:06,650 --> 01:25:13,120
the thousands of islands in the Caribbean;
no one could find her there. She no longer

944
01:25:13,120 --> 01:25:18,880
wanted to practise law. All she wanted to
do was reach her twenty-fifth birthday, and

945
01:25:18,880 --> 01:25:23,110
maybe her thirtieth too.

946
01:25:23,110 --> 01:25:24,110
***

947
01:25:24,110 --> 01:25:28,880
Croft spent a week waiting outside the offices
of Brim, Stearns and Kidlow. There were plenty

948
01:25:28,880 --> 01:25:34,230
of lawyers who looked as young as Garcia,
