1043
01:33:33,520 --> 01:33:36,170
'Where were you when you told him?'

1044
01:33:36,170 --> 01:33:38,600
'In his car.'

1045
01:33:38,600 --> 01:33:45,440
She shook her head slowly. 'I told you not
to tell anyone, didn't I? You think this is

1046
01:33:45,440 --> 01:33:52,280
all a game. It's not, Gray, it's real. This
isn't just a great newspaper story, which

1047
01:33:52,280 --> 01:33:59,949
is going to make Gray Grantham famous and
win him prizes. I've seen people die. God

1048
01:33:59,949 --> 01:34:06,690
knows how many times I've been close to death
myself. These people are dangerous, and they're

1049
01:34:06,690 --> 01:34:12,920
professionals. They know about you and the
Washington Post. They've probably been listening

1050
01:34:12,920 --> 01:34:18,330
to you since you wrote the first story about
this matter. They'll have microphones hidden

1051
01:34:18,330 --> 01:34:24,510
in your apartment, your car and your office.
It looks as though they've got microphones

1052
01:34:24,510 --> 01:34:31,770
in Keen's car as well. Do you understand what
I'm saying? Last night at dinner we tried

1053
01:34:31,770 --> 01:34:38,130
to pretend we were two normal people getting
to know each other. But that wasn't real:

1054
01:34:38,130 --> 01:34:41,860
this is real.'

1055
01:34:41,860 --> 01:34:47,530
She was right, of course. He felt like a schoolchild
in front of an angry teacher.

1056
01:34:47,530 --> 01:34:56,910
'You can stay here tonight,' she said, 'and
tomorrow I'll find you another small hotel.'

1057
01:34:56,910 --> 01:34:57,910
***

1058
01:34:57,910 --> 01:35:02,489
After breakfast the next morning she got on
the phone. She rang the Georgetown law school

1059
01:35:02,489 --> 01:35:09,300
and pretended to be from White and Blazevich.
She said that their computers were not working,

1060
01:35:09,300 --> 01:35:13,850
and that for the sake of her records she needed
to know which students had worked for White

1061
01:35:13,850 --> 01:35:20,900
and Blazevich last summer. She waited, with
her hand over the mouthpiece of the phone,

1062
01:35:20,900 --> 01:35:27,740
and looked at Gray. The secretary from the
law school came back on the phone. 'Seven

1063
01:35:27,740 --> 01:35:36,550
of them,' Darby said. 'Thank you.' She wrote
down their names. 'And do you have their addresses,

1064
01:35:36,550 --> 01:35:42,010
please? We need them for our records.' She
wrote down this information too.

1065
01:35:42,010 --> 01:35:49,570
'That was brilliant,' Gray said when she had
finished. 'Now all we need to do is find as

1066
01:35:49,570 --> 01:35:55,500
many of these students as we can, show them
your photograph of Garcia, and hope that one

1067
01:35:55,500 --> 01:35:59,369
of them recognizes him and can tell us his
real name.'

1068
01:35:59,369 --> 01:36:04,540
'Why couldn't we just wait outside the firm's
building until he came out, and then follow

1069
01:36:04,540 --> 01:36:08,190
him? That's what Croft was doing at Brim,
Stearns and Kidlow.'

1070
01:36:08,190 --> 01:36:15,280
'Too risky. It seems likely that White and
Blazevich were involved in some way in the

1071
01:36:15,280 --> 01:36:21,670
killings. There are people who know my face,
and we know they're looking for you too. What

1072
01:36:21,670 --> 01:36:28,580
if they're guarding White and Blazevich? They
would see us, and then we'd be dead.'

1073
01:36:28,580 --> 01:36:34,699
They hired a car and began to try to find
the seven students. Gray found two of them

1074
01:36:34,699 --> 01:36:40,920
at home and Darby spoke to another as he was
leaving a class at the school; none of them

1075
01:36:40,920 --> 01:36:49,010
recognized Garcia. They met at 10:45 and compared
notes. At eleven, students were leaving their

1076
01:36:49,010 --> 01:36:56,239
classes and she found another of the seven
students, but he too knew nothing. A fifth

1077
01:36:56,239 --> 01:37:01,699
was working in the library; she didn't like
answering Darby's questions, but she admitted

1078
01:37:01,699 --> 01:37:04,300
that she didn't know Garcia.

1079
01:37:04,300 --> 01:37:12,699
Only two left - Edward Linney and Judith Wilson.
Wilson was expected back at her apartment

1080
01:37:12,699 --> 01:37:18,650
at one o'clock, so Gray spent the rest of
the morning trying to find Linney, but he

1081
01:37:18,650 --> 01:37:24,970
was not at home and no one at the school seemed
to know where he was. They hadn't seen him

1082
01:37:24,970 --> 01:37:26,980
for several weeks.

1083
01:37:26,980 --> 01:37:35,400
They drove together to Judith Wilson's apartment.
She wasn't there at one, so they waited. She

1084
01:37:35,400 --> 01:37:41,739
arrived an hour later. Gray jumped out of
the car, ran up to her and caught her at her

1085
01:37:41,739 --> 01:37:48,119
front door. He showed her the photograph,
and Darby saw her shake her head.

1086
01:37:48,119 --> 01:37:54,969
'Linney had better be good,' he said as he
got back into the car. 'But where is he?'

1087
01:37:54,969 --> 01:38:02,639
'I hope we find him today,' she said, 'because
tomorrow I leave the country if we don't.'

1088
01:38:02,639 --> 01:38:09,921
Back at the law school, one of his fellow
students at last told them where he was: in

1089
01:38:09,921 --> 01:38:16,240
a private hospital. He was well on the way
to becoming an alcoholic, and his parents

1090
01:38:16,240 --> 01:38:22,170
had ordered him to spend some time there.
The nurse at the front desk of the hospital

1091
01:38:22,170 --> 01:38:29,690
told Gray that Mr Linney was in Room 22, but
refused to let him see him. Gray asked to

1092
01:38:29,690 --> 01:38:38,230
see the manager, and while the nurse was fetching
him Gray whispered to Darby, 'Room 22.'

1093
01:38:38,230 --> 01:38:44,340
She left the waiting-room and boldly walked
to his room. She knocked and went in. The

1094
01:38:44,340 --> 01:38:48,139
young man looked surprised to see her.

1095
01:38:48,139 --> 01:38:56,370
'I'm Sara Jacobs,' she said. 'I work for the
Washington Post. May I ask you a question?'

1096
01:38:56,370 --> 01:38:58,659
'Yes, but how did you get in?'

1097
01:38:58,659 --> 01:39:05,410
'I just walked in. You worked at White and
Blazevich last summer, didn't you? Do you

1098
01:39:05,410 --> 01:39:10,080
recognize this man?' She showed him the photograph.

1099
01:39:10,080 --> 01:39:19,080
'Yes, he's . . . what's his name? I can't
remember. He works in the oil and gas department.'

1100
01:39:19,080 --> 01:39:20,900
Darby held her breath.

1101
01:39:20,900 --> 01:39:28,010
Linney closed his eyes and thought. 'Morgan.
Yes, that's it. His surname is Morgan, but

1102
01:39:28,010 --> 01:39:33,010
I can't remember his first name. What's this
all about?'

1103
01:39:33,010 --> 01:39:38,750
'I'll tell you later,' Darby said, and left.

1104
01:39:38,750 --> 01:39:44,489
Gray was waiting for her back in the car.
She didn't say anything but immediately looked

1105
01:39:44,489 --> 01:39:53,420
at the notes she had taken in the law library.
There he was. 'Garcia is Curtis D. Morgan,'

1106
01:39:53,420 --> 01:39:59,670
she said. 'Let's go.'

1107
01:39:59,670 --> 01:40:02,480
CHAPTER FIFTEEN
Two Appointments

1108
01:40:02,480 --> 01:40:10,070
After five hours at sea in the small, fast
boat, every bone in Matthew Barr's body was

1109
01:40:10,070 --> 01:40:17,100
aching, and he was wet and cold. His only
companion had been a man called Larry, who

1110
01:40:17,100 --> 01:40:24,320
was extremely tall and looked very strong.
Larry had met him in Fort Lauderdale and had

1111
01:40:24,320 --> 01:40:27,969
not said a word to him since then.

1112
01:40:27,969 --> 01:40:34,130
They landed in a country Barr believed was
the Bahamas. A car took them to a small airfield,

1113
01:40:34,130 --> 01:40:41,260
where a Lear jet was waiting. The flight took
about forty-five minutes. Another car took

1114
01:40:41,260 --> 01:40:46,489
them to a large house. Barr had no idea where
they were.

1115
01:40:46,489 --> 01:40:52,690
Barr was met by a man who called himself Emil,
who led him round the outside of the house

1116
01:40:52,690 --> 01:40:54,270
to a sunroom.

1117
01:40:54,270 --> 01:41:01,501
'I'm afraid you must take off your shoes,'
Emil said with a polite smile, 'and be careful

1118
01:41:01,501 --> 01:41:03,680
not to step on the towels.'

1119
01:41:03,680 --> 01:41:09,540
Inside, Barr saw that towels were lying on
the floor of the sun- room, making paths around

1120
01:41:09,540 --> 01:41:17,580
the room. A door on the other side of the
room opened, and Victor Mattiece came in.

1121
01:41:17,580 --> 01:41:25,469
Barr stared. Mattiece was an extraordinary
sight. He was extremely thin, and had long

1122
01:41:25,469 --> 01:41:32,820
grey hair and a beard. He wore only a pair
of black sports shorts. His toenails were

1123
01:41:32,820 --> 01:41:38,870
yellow and very long. He looked completely
crazy.

1124
01:41:38,870 --> 01:41:48,880
'Sit over there,' he said, pointing at a chair.
'Don't step on the towels.'

1125
01:41:48,880 --> 01:41:58,560
When Barr was seated, Mattiece asked, 'What
do you want?' He was staring out of a window.

1126
01:41:58,560 --> 01:42:02,219
'The President sent me,' Barr began.

1127
01:42:02,219 --> 01:42:07,389
'He did not. Fletcher Coal sent you.'

1128
01:42:07,389 --> 01:42:14,719
'All right. We need to know whether the Pelican
Brief is true. Have you read it?'

1129
01:42:14,719 --> 01:42:16,909
'Have you?'

1130
01:42:16,909 --> 01:42:18,010
'Yes.'

1131
01:42:18,010 --> 01:42:21,790
'Does Mr Coal believe it to be true?'

1132
01:42:21,790 --> 01:42:29,659
'I don't know. He's very worried. That's why
I'm here, Mr Mattiece. We have to know.'

1133
01:42:29,659 --> 01:42:32,730
'What if it is true?'

1134
01:42:32,730 --> 01:42:36,900
'Then we have problems.'

1135
01:42:36,900 --> 01:42:43,410
Mattiece turned away from the window, looked
at Barr and said, 'Do you know what I think?

1136
01:42:43,410 --> 01:42:50,670
I think Coal is the problem. He let too many
people see the brief.'

1137
01:42:50,670 --> 01:42:56,980
Barr could not believe what he was hearing.
The man who had ordered so many deaths was

1138
01:42:56,980 --> 01:43:05,300
blaming someone else for the situation. 'Is
it true, Mr Mattiece? That's all I want to

1139
01:43:05,300 --> 01:43:07,790
know.'

1140
01:43:07,790 --> 01:43:15,420
Behind Barr, a door opened without a sound.
Larry, in his socks and avoiding the towels,

1141
01:43:15,420 --> 01:43:19,050
stepped silently into the room.

1142
01:43:19,050 --> 01:43:26,909
Mattiece walked over to the door and said
softly, 'Of course it's true.' He left the

1143
01:43:26,909 --> 01:43:30,650
sun-room and went into the garden.

1144
01:43:30,650 --> 01:43:34,030
Now what? Barr thought.

1145
01:43:34,030 --> 01:43:39,340
Larry put the rope round Barr's neck, and
Barr did not hear or feel anything until it

1146
01:43:39,340 --> 01:43:49,190
was too late. Mattiece did not want blood
on the floor, so Larry simply broke his neck.

1147
01:43:49,190 --> 01:43:50,190
***

1148
01:43:50,190 --> 01:43:54,820
They reached the building where White and
Blazevich's offices were before five o'clock.

1149
01:43:54,820 --> 01:44:00,950
She was wearing a dress, and Gray said she
looked just right. She could tell that he

1150
01:44:00,950 --> 01:44:07,119
liked the way she looked, and she found to
her surprise that it didn't make her angry,

1151
01:44:07,119 --> 01:44:10,659
just a little sad about Thomas.

1152
01:44:10,659 --> 01:44:16,280
She walked up to the secretary at the desk,
who said, 'Can I help you?'

1153
01:44:16,280 --> 01:44:25,099
'Yes, I have an appointment at five o'clock
with Curtis Morgan. My name is Dorothy Blythe.'

1154
01:44:25,099 --> 01:44:29,560
The secretary's mouth fell open and she said
nothing.

1155
01:44:29,560 --> 01:44:34,010
Darby's heart stopped. 'Is something the matter?'

1156
01:44:34,010 --> 01:44:40,760
'Can you wait a moment?' the secretary said.
She got up and disappeared into another room.

1157
01:44:40,760 --> 01:44:48,659
Run, Darby's mind was telling her, run! There's
something wrong here. But before she had time

1158
01:44:48,659 --> 01:44:52,570
to do anything, the secretary returned with
a man.

1159
01:44:52,570 --> 01:45:01,530
'Good afternoon,' he said. 'I'm Jarreld Schwabe,
one of the partners of the firm. You say you

1160
01:45:01,530 --> 01:45:04,230
have an appointment with Curtis Morgan?'

1161
01:45:04,230 --> 01:45:08,250
'Yes. Is there a problem?'

1162
01:45:08,250 --> 01:45:10,150
'There's nothing in his appointment book.'

1163
01:45:10,150 --> 01:45:13,960
'Well, that's your fault, not mine.'

1164
01:45:13,960 --> 01:45:16,969
'And what was the meeting about?'

1165
01:45:16,969 --> 01:45:24,360
She felt weak. 'I don't see why I have to
tell you that. Why can't I see Mr Morgan?'

1166
01:45:24,360 --> 01:45:27,460
'Because he's dead.'

1167
01:45:27,460 --> 01:45:31,220
She was in shock. 'Dead?'

1168
01:45:31,220 --> 01:45:40,010
'Yes,' Schwabe said. 'He was mugged in the
street. I'm sorry. I can see this has been

1169
01:45:40,010 --> 01:45:42,550
a shock for you.'

1170
01:45:42,550 --> 01:45:48,650
She decided to act really upset. She didn't
want them to ask any more questions; she wanted

1171
01:45:48,650 --> 01:45:55,420
them to think that she was just a weak young
woman. 'I'm sorry,' she said, 'I think I'd

1172
01:45:55,420 --> 01:45:59,620
better go. I'll phone again for another appointment.'

1173
01:45:59,620 --> 01:46:03,619
Schwabe led her to the lift himself.

1174
01:46:03,619 --> 01:46:10,970
Edwin Sneller knew that he and his men had
been wasting their time in New York; the place

1175
01:46:10,970 --> 01:46:18,670
was just too big. Then at last she moved some
money from her bank in New Orleans to Grantham's

1176
01:46:18,670 --> 01:46:25,040
bank in Washington. Sneller's client owned
the bank, so he received any information he

1177
01:46:25,040 --> 01:46:32,570
asked for. That meant that she was in Washington,
and that she and the reporter were working

1178
01:46:32,570 --> 01:46:38,580
together. He had two men with him, and he
had asked for more. They had to do the job

1179
01:46:38,580 --> 01:46:46,679
quickly. But he felt less confident without
Khamel. The girl had escaped so far, and she

1180
01:46:46,679 --> 01:46:53,080
could be hiding anywhere. He would start with
the Washington Post building: Grantham had

1181
01:46:53,080 --> 01:46:57,320
to come back there some time.

1182
01:46:57,320 --> 01:46:58,320
***

1183
01:46:58,320 --> 01:47:02,159
Gray found Curtis D. Morgan's address in the
suburbs, and they drove out together to the

1184
01:47:02,159 --> 01:47:10,409
house. Mrs Morgan's father, however, refused
to let them in to see her. Gray left his business

1185
01:47:10,409 --> 01:47:16,530
card, so that she could call him if she wanted
to. He told her father that Morgan had spoken

1186
01:47:16,530 --> 01:47:19,610
to him three times just before he died.

1187
01:47:19,610 --> 01:47:26,230
'Is that the end of Garcia?' Darby asked as
they drove away.

1188
01:47:26,230 --> 01:47:33,550
'We'll see tomorrow,' he said. 'How do you
feel at the moment? Do you feel safe? I'll

1189
01:47:33,550 --> 01:47:38,580
be glad to sleep in your room tonight, just
like I did in New York.'

1190
01:47:38,580 --> 01:47:47,060
'But I don't have a sofa here,' she said.
'Where would you sleep?' She was smiling and

1191
01:47:47,060 --> 01:47:56,429
this was a good sign. But then she remembered
Callahan. 'I'm not ready, Gray. I'm sorry.'

1192
01:47:56,429 --> 01:48:01,620
She rested her head on his shoulder while
he drove the car. 'I'm still frightened to

1193
01:48:01,620 --> 01:48:07,320
death,' she said.

1194
01:48:07,320 --> 01:48:12,409
CHAPTER SIXTEEN
Morgan's Story

1195
01:48:12,409 --> 01:48:19,020
Beverly Morgan called Gray at four o'clock
the next morning. 'My father would be angry

1196
01:48:19,020 --> 01:48:24,630
with me if he knew I was calling,' she said.
'The reporters were horrible to us after Curtis

1197
01:48:24,630 --> 01:48:29,000
was killed. But I need to talk to someone.'

1198
01:48:29,000 --> 01:48:33,869
She asked him how he knew her husband, and
Gray explained about his phone calls, and

1199
01:48:33,869 --> 01:48:40,119
the murders of Rosenberg and Jensen. He spoke
to her patiently for a long time, until he

1200
01:48:40,119 --> 01:48:41,550
won her confidence.

1201
01:48:41,550 --> 01:48:45,179
'What do you think he knew?' she asked.

1202
01:48:45,179 --> 01:48:52,170
'I have no idea. If he had written something
down on paper, where would it be?'

1203
01:48:52,170 --> 01:48:57,810
'In our lock-box in the bank. But that's where
all his legal papers were, so I've already

1204
01:48:57,810 --> 01:49:03,770
looked in there. I did find another key in
his desk, though, last Saturday.'

1205
01:49:03,770 --> 01:49:07,040
Gray held his breath. 'A key to another lock-box?'

1206
01:49:07,040 --> 01:49:16,619
'Yes, a box at First Columbia Bank. That's
odd, because we've never used that bank. I

1207
01:49:16,619 --> 01:49:21,349
wasn't in a hurry to go to the bank and look
in the box, because I already had all his

1208
01:49:21,349 --> 01:49:26,639
legal papers. Maybe it was even something
I wouldn't want to see.'

1209
01:49:26,639 --> 01:49:30,929
'Would you like me to look in the box for
you?' Gray asked.

1210
01:49:30,929 --> 01:49:35,250
'I hoped you would say that. Yes, please.'

1211
01:49:35,250 --> 01:49:36,800
'I'll come round and get the key now'

1212
01:49:36,800 --> 01:49:39,139
***

1213
01:49:39,139 --> 01:49:45,650
He and Darby drove to the bank the next morning.
Mrs Morgan had given Gray written permission

1214
01:49:45,650 --> 01:49:51,920
to open the lock-box, so the clerk let them
into the strong-room. It didn't take them

1215
01:49:51,920 --> 01:49:58,090
long to empty the box: all it held was a thin
envelope.

1216
01:49:58,090 --> 01:50:03,909
Darby opened the envelope when they were back
in the car. Inside was a document written

1217
01:50:03,909 --> 01:50:12,650
by Morgan and properly signed by a legal witness.
The document started: 'Since you are reading

1218
01:50:12,650 --> 01:50:19,120
this, I am probably dead.' It was a powerful
first sentence.

1219
01:50:19,120 --> 01:50:27,159
In the document Morgan described who he was
and where he worked. He said that he often

1220
01:50:27,159 --> 01:50:34,180
worked for one of the firm's clients who was
called Victor Mattiece. The partner in charge

1221
01:50:34,180 --> 01:50:42,170
of Mr Mattiece was F. Sims Wakefield. Morgan
explained the Louisiana case and how important

1222
01:50:42,170 --> 01:50:48,989
it was to Mr Mattiece. It was important to
White and Blazevich too, since Mattiece had

1223
01:50:48,989 --> 01:50:52,750
promised them a share of the profits from
the oil.

1224
01:50:52,750 --> 01:51:01,639
On or about 28 September, the document continued,
Morgan had been in Wakefield's office collecting

1225
01:51:01,639 --> 01:51:09,300
some files. When he returned to his own office,
he found that by mistake he had picked up

1226
01:51:09,300 --> 01:51:16,150
a note from Wakefield's desk together with
the files. A copy of the note was joined on

1227
01:51:16,150 --> 01:51:25,349
to Morgan's document. The note was dated 28
September and was from Marty Velmano, another

1228
01:51:25,349 --> 01:51:34,750
partner. It read: Sims: Tell our client that
the Court will be easier on him if Rosenberg

1229
01:51:34,750 --> 01:51:44,889
is retired. The second retirement is a bit
unusual - it is Jensen (who, as you know,

1230
01:51:44,889 --> 01:51:54,489
has those other problems). The note amazed
and frightened Morgan. Realizing its importance,

1231
01:51:54,489 --> 01:52:00,659
he made a copy of it and returned the original
to the bottom of the pile of files.

1232
01:52:00,659 --> 01:52:07,840
Ten minutes later Wakefield came into his
office, looking pale and worried. They found

1233
01:52:07,840 --> 01:52:16,940
the note under the files and Wakefield asked
Morgan if he had read it; Morgan said no.

1234
01:52:16,940 --> 01:52:22,440
Wakefield looked at him very closely, but
seemed satisfied.

1235
01:52:22,440 --> 01:52:28,989
That night he left the papers on his desk
very tidy. The next morning he could see that

1236
01:52:28,989 --> 01:52:36,530
someone had searched his desk. He began to
see Velmano in Wakefield's office more than

1237
01:52:36,530 --> 01:52:42,300
usual. Wakefield stopped him working for Mattiece.

1238
01:52:42,300 --> 01:52:50,969
Then Rosenberg and Jensen were killed. He
was sure that Mattiece had ordered the killings.

1239
01:52:50,969 --> 01:52:57,110
He thought that people were following him.
He had decided to hide his copy of the note

1240
01:52:57,110 --> 01:53:05,710
together with this document in a bank, in
case he was killed. He was very frightened.

1241
01:53:05,710 --> 01:53:10,020
That was the end of the document.

1242
01:53:10,020 --> 01:53:11,020
***

1243
01:53:11,020 --> 01:53:16,239
The thin-faced man watched the car come fast
round the corner and park illegally outside

1244
01:53:16,239 --> 01:53:23,599
the Post building. The man and the woman jumped
out of the car and ran past him into the building.

1245
01:53:23,599 --> 01:53:30,599
He had a gun inside his jacket, but it all
happened too fast.

1246
01:53:30,599 --> 01:53:31,599
***

1247
01:53:31,599 --> 01:53:38,280
Smith Keen and the Post's lawyer, Vincent
Litsky, read through Morgan's document. When

1248
01:53:38,280 --> 01:53:46,020
they had finished, Gray said, 'Well, gentlemen,
there's your independent witness. Can we print

1249
01:53:46,020 --> 01:53:49,170
Darby's story now?'

1250
01:53:49,170 --> 01:53:54,670
Keen and Litsky looked at each other. Keen
left the office for a few minutes to speak

1251
01:53:54,670 --> 01:54:03,780
to the newspaper's owner. When he came back
he said, 'OK, Gray. We do the story. How long

1252
01:54:03,780 --> 01:54:06,810
will it take you to write it?'

1253
01:54:06,810 --> 01:54:12,679
'I already know the shape of it,' Gray replied.
'I only have to write the details. It should

1254
01:54:12,679 --> 01:54:15,760
take me about two hours.'

1255
01:54:15,760 --> 01:54:22,869
'It's eleven o'clock now,' Keen said. 'Try
to finish it by three. Litsky needs time to

1256
01:54:22,869 --> 01:54:26,280
read it before we print.'

1257
01:54:26,280 --> 01:54:32,750
With Darby's help, he finished the story on
time. Keen and Litsky read it and made some

1258
01:54:32,750 --> 01:54:37,610
changes. Darby was watching something out
of the window.

1259
01:54:37,610 --> 01:54:44,860
'When I've rewritten the story,' Gray said,
when Keen and Litsky had finished, 'I have

1260
01:54:44,860 --> 01:54:46,659
to make some phone calls.'

1261
01:54:46,659 --> 01:54:51,949
'We'll be back at half past three,' Keen said.

1262
01:54:51,949 --> 01:54:58,619
'They're outside,' Darby said softly, when
Keen and Litsky had left the room.

1263
01:54:58,619 --> 01:55:00,090
'Who are?'

1264
01:55:00,090 --> 01:55:06,699
'I was watching a man standing on the corner.
He looks innocent enough; he's just standing

1265
01:55:06,699 --> 01:55:12,930
there drinking coffee from a cup. But he's
been there a long time - I saw him earlier

1266
01:55:12,930 --> 01:55:20,239
as well. And just now, when you were talking,
I saw the short man who chased me last week

1267
01:55:20,239 --> 01:55:25,889
come up to the coffee-drinker. They talked
for a minute and then the short man disappeared

1268
01:55:25,889 --> 01:55:33,710
again. They're just waiting for us to leave
the building.'

1269
01:55:33,710 --> 01:55:39,070
CHAPTER SEVENTEEN
Time to Trust Someone

1270
01:55:39,070 --> 01:55:43,340
The first phone call was to a friend of Grantham
at the FBI.

1271
01:55:43,340 --> 01:55:48,320
'Phil, this is Gray Grantham. I've got the
recorder on.'

1272
01:55:48,320 --> 01:55:51,719
'That sounds serious. Go on.'

1273
01:55:51,719 --> 01:55:57,829
'We're going to print a story tomorrow about
the Rosenberg and Jensen killings. We're going

1274
01:55:57,829 --> 01:56:02,989
to name Victor Mattiece as the man behind
the killings, and also two of his lawyers

1275
01:56:02,989 --> 01:56:10,040
here in Washington. We'll connect this story
with the killing of Verheek in New Orleans.

1276
01:56:10,040 --> 01:56:15,599
We believe the FBI knew about Mattiece early
on but refused to investigate at the request

1277
01:56:15,599 --> 01:56:24,219
of the White House. We want to give you the
chance to comment.' There was silence. 'Phil,

1278
01:56:24,219 --> 01:56:26,119
are you there?'

1279
01:56:26,119 --> 01:56:29,000
'Yes, I think so.'

1280
01:56:29,000 --> 01:56:30,780
'Any comment?'

1281
01:56:30,780 --> 01:56:35,869
'I'm sure we will have a comment, but I'll
have to call you back.'

1282
01:56:35,869 --> 01:56:39,540
'OK. I'll look forward to it.'

1283
01:56:39,540 --> 01:56:45,389
In fact it was Voyles himself who called back,
about ten minutes later. He demanded to speak

1284
01:56:45,389 --> 01:56:46,620
to Smith Keen.

1285
01:56:46,620 --> 01:56:52,820
'What are you doing, Smith?' he said. 'We're
still investigating Mattiece. It's too early

1286
01:56:52,820 --> 01:56:55,500
to be sure. What have you got?'

1287
01:56:55,500 --> 01:57:00,480
'Does the name Darby Shaw mean anything to
you?' Keen asked.

1288
01:57:00,480 --> 01:57:01,480
'Yes.'

1289
01:57:01,480 --> 01:57:07,449
'We have the Pelican Brief, Denton, and I'm
sitting here looking at Darby Shaw.'

1290
01:57:07,449 --> 01:57:09,980
'I was afraid she was dead.'

1291
01:57:09,980 --> 01:57:15,449
'No, she's not. And she and Gray Grantham
have an independent witness to support the

1292
01:57:15,449 --> 01:57:18,500
brief. It's a big story, Denton.'

1293
01:57:18,500 --> 01:57:24,320
'We need to meet. I'll come round in twenty
minutes.'

1294
01:57:24,320 --> 01:57:26,119
'OK.'

1295
01:57:26,119 --> 01:57:31,750
Keen put the phone down and smiled. He was
amused at the idea of the great F. Denton

1296
01:57:31,750 --> 01:57:36,510
Voyles coming round to his office for a meeting.

1297
01:57:36,510 --> 01:57:42,560
The next phone call Gray made was to Fletcher
Coal in the White House. Coal agreed that

1298
01:57:42,560 --> 01:57:47,969
Mattiece had given large amounts of money
towards the President's election, but denied

1299
01:57:47,969 --> 01:57:53,400
that Mattiece and the President were close
friends. He had to admit that he was familiar

1300
01:57:53,400 --> 01:57:59,260
with the Pelican Brief. When Gray asked why
there had not been an immediate investigation

1301
01:57:59,260 --> 01:58:06,389
of Mattiece, Coal angrily denied that the
White House had tried to slow down such an

1302
01:58:06,389 --> 01:58:07,389
investigation.

1303
01:58:07,389 --> 01:58:14,260
Then Voyles arrived with K. O. Lewis. Keen
took him into his own office and gave him

1304
01:58:14,260 --> 01:58:21,469
a copy of the story to read while Gray made
the third phone call. He rang White and Blazevich

1305
01:58:21,469 --> 01:58:27,449
and was put through to Marty Velmano. For
the third time he explained that he was recording

1306
01:58:27,449 --> 01:58:29,400
the conversation.

1307
01:58:29,400 --> 01:58:35,840
'Mr Velmano,' Gray said, 'we're printing a
story in the morning which names your client

1308
01:58:35,840 --> 01:58:40,880
Victor Mattiece as the man behind thekillings
of Rosenberg and Jensen.'

1309
01:58:40,880 --> 01:58:49,540
'Good!' said Velmano. 'We'll take you to court.
By the time we're finished, Mr Mattiece will

1310
01:58:49,540 --> 01:58:52,159
own the Washington Post.'

1311
01:58:52,159 --> 01:58:58,989
'Mr Velmano, we have a copy of the Pelican
Brief. Have you heard of it?'

1312
01:58:58,989 --> 01:59:00,139
Silence.

1313
01:59:00,139 --> 01:59:09,099
'We also have a copy of a note you sent to
Sims Wakefield on 28 September. In the note

1314
01:59:09,099 --> 01:59:14,820
you suggested that your client's position
would be a lot better without Rosenberg and

1315
01:59:14,820 --> 01:59:16,619
Jensen on the Supreme Court.'

1316
01:59:16,619 --> 01:59:17,760
Silence.

1317
01:59:17,760 --> 01:59:23,440
'Mr Velmano, are you there?'

1318
01:59:23,440 --> 01:59:24,570
'Yes.'

1319
01:59:24,570 --> 01:59:31,320
'We wanted to give you the chance to comment.
Do you have any comment?'

1320
01:59:31,320 --> 01:59:37,720
'You're going to destroy me,' Velmano said.

1321
01:59:37,720 --> 01:59:38,720
***

1322
01:59:38,720 --> 01:59:44,469
Voyles and Lewis entered the room with Smith
Keen. Keen introduced them to Darby and Gray.

1323
01:59:44,469 --> 01:59:50,420
Voyles smiled at Darby and said, 'So you're
the one who started all this.'

1324
01:59:50,420 --> 01:59:55,810
'No, sir,' she said, 'I think it was Mattiece.'

1325
01:59:55,810 --> 02:00:02,660
They sat around a table. Voyles had a piece
of paper. He said, 'I'm going to read you

1326
02:00:02,660 --> 02:00:09,150
something. This is official, and you can use
it in your paper. Anything else Lewis or I

1327
02:00:09,150 --> 02:00:15,500
say is unofficial, and you can't use it. Is
that clear?'

1328
02:00:15,500 --> 02:00:17,330
Keen and Grantham said yes.

1329
02:00:17,330 --> 02:00:25,580
'All right,' Voyles said. 'We received a copy
of the Pelican Brief two weeks ago and showed

1330
02:00:25,580 --> 02:00:31,780
it to the White House on the same day. It
was personally delivered by K. O. Lewis to

1331
02:00:31,780 --> 02:00:41,030
Fletcher Coal. Eric East was also present
at the meeting. We thought it was worth investigation,

1332
02:00:41,030 --> 02:00:48,889
but nothing happened for six days, until Gavin
Verheek was murdered in New Orleans. The FBI

1333
02:00:48,889 --> 02:00:56,440
began a full investigation into Victor Mattiece,
involving over four hundred men. We believe

1334
02:00:56,440 --> 02:01:02,810
Victor Mattiece to be the main suspect in
the murders of Rosenberg, Jensen, Thomas Callahan

1335
02:01:02,810 --> 02:01:06,489
and Verheek, and we are trying to find him.'

1336
02:01:06,489 --> 02:01:12,920
'Did the White House interfere with your investigation
of Mattiece?' Grantham asked.

1337
02:01:12,920 --> 02:01:21,020
'This is now unofficial,' Voyles said. 'You
can't use it. OK?'

1338
02:01:21,020 --> 02:01:22,440
'OK.'

1339
02:01:22,440 --> 02:01:29,180
'Yes, the President asked me not to investigate
Mattiece. He said it could be embarrassing

1340
02:01:29,180 --> 02:01:34,510
to the Government. I recorded the conversation.'

1341
02:01:34,510 --> 02:01:39,020
They could hardly believe what they were hearing.
He recorded the President!

1342
02:01:39,020 --> 02:01:46,869
'I will not allow anyone to hear that recording,'
Voyles continued, 'unless the President denies

1343
02:01:46,869 --> 02:01:53,452
what I have just told you. Anyway, will you
use the official story I've given you? Will

1344
02:01:53,452 --> 02:01:59,420
you put Coal's name there on the front page
along with everyone else?'

1345
02:01:59,420 --> 02:02:03,831
'Yes, I think he belongs there,' Keen said.

1346
02:02:03,831 --> 02:02:12,470
'Good,' said Voyles. 'Can you give me some
early copies of the newspaper tomorrow morning?

1347
02:02:12,470 --> 02:02:16,250
I want to take them round to him myself and
watch his face.'

1348
02:02:16,250 --> 02:02:23,349
'He'll take the blame,' Keen said. 'It will
be the end of his career, but he'll make the

1349
02:02:23,349 --> 02:02:25,320
President look innocent.'

1350
02:02:25,320 --> 02:02:34,360
'Yes, I think you're right,' said Voyles.
'Now, I'd like to speak to Miss Shaw alone,

1351
02:02:34,360 --> 02:02:37,159
please, if that's all right with her.'

1352
02:02:37,159 --> 02:02:40,500
'OK,' she said, 'but Grantham stays.'

1353
02:02:40,500 --> 02:02:43,780
'All right.'

1354
02:02:43,780 --> 02:02:51,140
When everyone else had left the room, Voyles
asked, 'What are you going to do next?'

1355
02:02:51,140 --> 02:02:55,030
'First tell me who killed Gavin Verheek,'
she said.

1356
02:02:55,030 --> 02:03:01,450
'It was Khamel. And Khamel was the one who
was shot in the head as you were holding his

1357
02:03:01,450 --> 02:03:03,050
hand by the river.'

1358
02:03:03,050 --> 02:03:05,140
'Who killed him?'

1359
02:03:05,140 --> 02:03:11,600
'We think it was someone from the CIA. We
know the CIA were investigating Mattiece in

1360
02:03:11,600 --> 02:03:17,829
a small way. In his oil business Mattiece
had connections with some unfriendly Arab

1361
02:03:17,829 --> 02:03:24,510
countries, so the CIA were already keeping
an eye on him. When they saw a copy of the

1362
02:03:24,510 --> 02:03:30,510
Pelican Brief they sent a few men down to
New Orleans to look after you.'

1363
02:03:30,510 --> 02:03:36,980
Darby got up and went to the window. It was
dark outside now. 'They didn't do a very good

1364
02:03:36,980 --> 02:03:42,261
job, then,' she said. 'There are men out there
now who have been following me for a week

1365
02:03:42,261 --> 02:03:49,869
or more. One of them chased me in New Orleans,
so I don't think he's CIA. Mattiece is so

1366
02:03:49,869 --> 02:03:55,920
crazy that he'll go on trying to kill me even
after he goes to prison - if you catch him.'

1367
02:03:55,920 --> 02:04:02,630
'We can help,' Voyles said. 'We can get you
out of the country.'

1368
02:04:02,630 --> 02:04:09,920
It was time to trust someone. She took a deep
breath. 'All right,' she said.

1369
02:04:09,920 --> 02:04:14,000
'I'll go and make the arrangements,' Voyles
said.

1370
02:04:14,000 --> 02:04:20,969
Alone in the room, Darby walked into Gray's
arms. 'It's going to be all right now,' he

1371
02:04:20,969 --> 02:04:26,020
said, holding her. 'It's over. You're safe.'

1372
02:04:26,020 --> 02:04:34,670
'I'm going alone, Gray,' she said. 'I'll call
you when I'm ready.'

1373
02:04:34,670 --> 02:04:37,330
CHAPTER EIGHTEEN
Away From It All

1374
02:04:37,330 --> 02:04:46,510
By 11 p.m. only four lawyers remained in the
offices of White and Blazevich. They were

1375
02:04:46,510 --> 02:04:55,530
Velmano, Sims Wakefield, Jarreld Schwabe and
a retired partner named Frank Cortz.

1376
02:04:55,530 --> 02:05:03,969
Cortz finished a phone conversation with one
of Victor Mattiece's staff. 'That was Strider,'

1377
02:05:03,969 --> 02:05:12,929
he said. 'They're in Cairo, in some hotel.
Mattiece won't talk to us and, of course,

1378
02:05:12,929 --> 02:05:19,809
he isn't coming back over here. Strider says
he's behaving very strangely. They've told

1379
02:05:19,809 --> 02:05:25,929
the boys with the guns to leave town immediately.
The chase is over.'

1380
02:05:25,929 --> 02:05:30,369
'So what are we supposed to do?' asked Wakefield.

1381
02:05:30,369 --> 02:05:38,350
'We're on our own,' said Cortz. 'Mattiece
isn't going to help us.'

1382
02:05:38,350 --> 02:05:46,550
There was silence around the table as they
all looked into the future. Then Velmano said,

1383
02:05:46,550 --> 02:05:53,980
'Grantham only mentioned me and Sims. You
two may be OK. And I've got enough money saved

1384
02:05:53,980 --> 02:05:56,699
to spend the rest of my life hiding in Europe.'

1385
02:05:56,699 --> 02:06:05,579
'It's all right for you,' Wakefield said.
'I can't hide. I've got a wife and six children.'

1386
02:06:05,579 --> 02:06:12,760
'I think you should go home and tell your
wife what to expect,' Velmano said.

1387
02:06:12,760 --> 02:06:20,010
'I can't do that,' Wakefield said. He got
up and left the room.

1388
02:06:20,010 --> 02:06:29,429
A minute later they heard the sound of a single
gunshot from his office.

1389
02:06:29,429 --> 02:06:30,429
***

1390
02:06:30,429 --> 02:06:34,489
After eight days in the sun of the Virgin
Islands her skin was brown enough and her

1391
02:06:34,489 --> 02:06:40,570
hair was returning to its natural colour.
She walked miles up and down the beaches and

1392
02:06:40,570 --> 02:06:47,750
ate nothing except fish and fruit. She slept
a lot the first few days.

1393
02:06:47,750 --> 02:06:53,380
She looked at her wrist and then remembered
that her watch was in a bag somewhere. She

1394
02:06:53,380 --> 02:07:01,030
didn't need it here. She woke with the sun
and went to bed after dark. But now she was

1395
02:07:01,030 --> 02:07:04,370
waiting, so she had looked at her wrist.

1396
02:07:04,370 --> 02:07:11,639
It was almost dark when the taxi stopped at
the end of the small road. He got out, paid

1397
02:07:11,639 --> 02:07:17,910
the driver and looked at the lights as the
car disappeared back up the road. He had one

1398
02:07:17,910 --> 02:07:24,349
bag. He could see a light from the house between
the trees at the edge of the beach, and he

1399
02:07:24,349 --> 02:07:32,630
walked towards it. He didn't know what to
expect. He knew how he felt about her, but

1400
02:07:32,630 --> 02:07:35,770
did she feel the same?

1401
02:07:35,770 --> 02:07:42,329
She was waiting at the back of the house,
looking out to sea, with a drink in her hand.

1402
02:07:42,329 --> 02:07:47,760
She smiled at him, put down her drink and
let him come to her.

1403
02:07:47,760 --> 02:07:53,079
They kissed for a long minute. 'You're late,'
she said.

1404
02:07:53,079 --> 02:07:59,580
'This is not the easiest place to find,' Gray
said. 'Even when you have directions.'

1405
02:07:59,580 --> 02:08:08,059
'I know,' she said. 'That's the idea. It's
beautiful, though, isn't it?'

1406
02:08:08,059 --> 02:08:10,829
'It is. You are too.'

1407
02:08:10,829 --> 02:08:14,869
'Let's go for a walk,' she said.

1408
02:08:14,869 --> 02:08:20,940
He changed into a pair of shorts and they
walked together on the beach, hand in hand.

1409
02:08:20,940 --> 02:08:24,280
'You left early,' she said.

1410
02:08:24,280 --> 02:08:31,119
'I got tired of it. I've written a story a
day since the big one, and they kept wanting

1411
02:08:31,119 --> 02:08:38,239
more. I was working eighteen hours a day.
Yesterday I said goodbye.'

1412
02:08:38,239 --> 02:08:43,059
'I haven't seen a paper for days,' she said.

1413
02:08:43,059 --> 02:08:50,159
'Coal's finished. The President will be OK.
I don't think he did anything really bad;

1414
02:08:50,159 --> 02:08:56,500
he's just stupid. He won't get reelected,
though. You read about Wakefield?'

1415
02:08:56,500 --> 02:09:00,570
'Yes, that was in the last paper I saw.'

1416
02:09:00,570 --> 02:09:07,710
'They've got Schwabe. They want Velmano too,
but he's disappeared. Of course Mattiece is

1417
02:09:07,710 --> 02:09:13,130
in deep trouble, and they're after four of
his men too.'

1418
02:09:13,130 --> 02:09:17,960
They walked in silence along the beach. She
put her arm round his waist and he pulled

1419
02:09:17,960 --> 02:09:28,949
her closer. 'I've missed you,' she said softly.
He breathed deeply, but said nothing. 'How

1420
02:09:28,949 --> 02:09:31,929
long will you stay?' she asked.

1421
02:09:31,929 --> 02:09:40,739
'I don't know. A couple of weeks. Maybe a
year. It depends on you.'

1422
02:09:40,739 --> 02:09:45,710
'Let's take it a month at a time. OK, Gray?'

1423
02:09:45,710 --> 02:09:46,710
'Perfect.'

1424
02:09:46,710 --> 02:09:47,100
- THE END -

